# Building a ggplot {.inverse}

> Step by step

## Step 1: `ggplot(data)`

The `ggplot()` function initializes a ggplot object. Every ggplot needs this function.

. . .

:::{.columns}

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(gapminder)
```
:::


- Empty plot because we haven't told ggplot what to put on the axes yet

:::

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](ggplot_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=604.8}
:::
:::


:::

:::

## Step 2: add `aes(x, y)`

The **aes**thetics define how data variables are mapped to plot properties.

. . .

:::{.columns}

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  gapminder,
  aes(
    x = gdpPercap,
    y = lifeExp
  )
)
```
:::


- Axes are set up, but no data points yet
- Scales adapt automatically to the range of the data

:::

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](ggplot_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=604.8}
:::
:::


:::

:::


## Step 3: add a `geom`

`geoms` define how data points are represented. There are many different geoms to chose from

![from [ggplot cheatsheet](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rstudio/cheatsheets/master/data-visualization-2.1.pdf)](img/day2/geom_ggplot.png){width=60%}

## Step 3: add a `geom`

:::{.columns}

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  gapminder,
  aes(
    x = gdpPercap,
    y = lifeExp
  )
) +
  geom_point()
```
:::


- New layers are added with `+`
- `data` and `aes` defined in `ggplot` call are inherited to all plot layers

:::{.fragment}
Does this depend on the continent?
:::

:::

:::{.column width="50%"}


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](ggplot_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=604.8}
:::
:::


:::

:::

## Local vs. global aesthetics

:::{.columns}

:::{.column width="50%"}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot() +
  geom_point(
    data = gapminder,
    aes(
      x = gdpPercap,
      y = lifeExp
    )
  )
```
:::


- `data` and/or `aes` can also be local to a layer
- You need to explicitly specify the data argument with `data = ...`

:::{.fragment}

Here, it does not make a difference in the result.

:::

:::

:::{.column width="50%"}


